{{EngvarB|date=July 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} [[File:HastingsRashdall.jpg|thumb|right|Hastings Rashdall]] '''Hastings Rashdall''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (24 June 1858, London – 9 February 1924, [[Worthing]]) was an English philosopher, theologian, and historian. He expounded a theory known as [[Utilitarianism#Ideal utilitarianism|ideal utilitarianism]], and he was a major historian of the universities of the [[Middle Ages]].<ref>"Rashdall, Hastings," ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', where Rashdall's ''The Universities of Europe in the Middle Ages'' is referred to as "a standard work."</ref>
==Biography== Rashdall was the son of an [[Anglican]] priest. He was educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]]<ref>'RASHDALL, Very Rev. Hastings', Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920–2015; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U201990, accessed 20 March 2015]</ref> and received a scholarship for [[New College, Oxford|New College]], Oxford. After short tenures at [[St David's University College]] and [[University College, Durham]], Rashdall was made a Fellow of first [[Hertford College, Oxford]], then [[New College, Oxford]], and dedicates his main work, ''[[The Theory of Good and Evil]]'' (1907), to the memory of his teachers [[Thomas Hill Green]] and [[Henry Sidgwick]].
The dedication is appropriate, for the particular version of utilitarianism put forward by Rashdall owes elements to both Green and Sidgwick.<ref>"Rashdall, Hastings," ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography.''</ref> Whereas he holds that the concepts of good and value are logically prior to that of right, he gives right a more than instrumental significance. His idea of good owes more to Green than to the hedonistic utilitarians. "The ideal of human life is not the mere juxtaposition of distinct goods, but a whole in which each good is made different by the presence of others." Rashdall has been eclipsed as a moral philosopher by [[G. E. Moore]], who advocated similar views in his earlier work ''[[Principia Ethica]]'' (1903). Rashdall was also a [[George Berkeley|Berkeleyan]], believing in metaphysical [[idealism]].
His historical study, ''The Universities of Europe in the Middle Ages'',<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Quarterly Review|title=Review of ''The European Universities of the Middle Ages'' by Hastings Rashdall|volume=183|date=April 1896|pages=445–472|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044092526664;view=1up;seq=455}}</ref> was described in the introduction to its recent reprinting as "one of the first comparative works on the subject" whose "scope and breadth has assured its place as a key work in intellectual history."
His ''The Idea of Atonement in Christian Theology'' surveyed different approaches to the Christian doctrine of [[Atonement in Christianity|atonement]], concluding with an influential defence of the "subjective" theory of the atonement that Rashdall attributed to both [[Peter Abelard]] and [[Peter Lombard]]. Rashdall argued that the "objective" view of the atonement associated with [[Anselm of Canterbury]] was inadequate, and that the most authentically Christian doctrine was that Christ's life was a demonstration of God's love so profound that Christ was willing to die rather than compromise his character. This in turn inspires believers to emulate his character and his intimacy with the Father.<ref>''The Idea of Atonement in Christian Theology'', pp. 437–47</ref>
Rashdall received the degree [[Doctor of Letters]] (DL) from New College, Oxford, in October 1901.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=University intelligence |day_of_week=Friday |date=18 October 1901 |page_number=4 |issue=36589| }}</ref>
He was president of the [[Aristotelian Society]] from 1904 to 1907, a member of the [[Christian Social Union (Church of England)|Christian Social Union]] from its inception in 1890, and was an influential [[Anglican]] modernist theologian of the time, being appointed to a canonry in 1909.
He was Dean of [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] from 1917 to 1924, and died of cancer in [[Worthing]] in 1924.<ref>''Dean Rashdall.'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Monday, 11 February 1924; pg. 17; Issue 43572</ref>
==Selected works== *{{cite book | last = Rashdall | first = Hastings | title = The Universities of Europe in the Middle Ages, ''2 vols. in 3 parts'' | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4m-ISQAACAAJ&dq=isbn:9781108018135&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LusmT9ykHYf10gHE9IW3CA&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA | origyear = 1895 | year = 2010 | publisher = Cambridge University Press [orig. Oxford: Clarendon Press] | location = Cambridge | isbn = 978-1-108-01813-5 }} *[https://archive.org/details/doctrineanddevel00rashuoft ''Doctrine and Development: University Sermons''] (1898) *[https://archive.org/stream/newcollege00rashrich#page/n9/mode/2up ''New College''] (with [[Robert Rait]], 1901) *[https://archive.org/details/christusineccles00rashuoft ''Christus in Ecclesia: Sermons on the Church and its Institutions''] (1904) *[http://fair-use.org/hastings-rashdall/the-theory-of-good-and-evil/ ''The Theory of Good and Evil''] (1907) *[https://archive.org/details/rashdallsethics00rashuoft ''Ethics''] (undated) *[https://archive.org/details/philosophyandrel00rashuoft ''Philosophy and Religion''] (1910) *[https://archive.org/details/isconscienceane00rashgoog ''Is Conscience an Emotion? Three Lectures on recent ethical theories''] (1914) *[https://archive.org/details/consciencechrist00rashrich ''Conscience and Christ: Six Lectures on Christian Ethics''] (1916) *[https://archive.org/details/atonementchristi00rashuoft ''The Idea of Atonement in Christian Theology''] (London: Macmillan, 1919) *[https://archive.org/details/kingscollegelect00matt ''The Moral Argument for Personal Immortality''] in ''King's College Lectures on Immortality'' (1920) *[https://archive.org/details/MN40227ucmf_1 ''God and Man''] 1930
