{{Sangam literature}}
'''Nariverūuth Thalaiyār''' ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: நரிவெரூஉத் தலையார்) was a poet of the [[Sangam period]], to whom 5 verses of the Sangam literature have been attributed, including verse 33 of the [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]].<ref name="Vedanayagam_Urai">{{cite book | last = Vedanayagam | first = Rama | author-link = | title = திருவள்ளுவ மாலை மூலமும் எளிய உரை விளக்கமும் [Tiruvalluva Maalai: Moolamum Eliya Urai Vilakkamum] | publisher = Manimekalai Prasuram | series = | volume = | edition = 1 | date = 2017 | location = Chennai | pages =48–49 | language = Tamil | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>
==Biography== Nariveruvu Thalaiyar was known for his sickness, which was cured by the [[Chera dynasty|Chera king]] Cheraman Karuvuraeriya Olvat Kopperuncheral Irumporai.<ref name="SangaIlakkiyam_2">{{cite book | last = Kowmareeshwari (Ed.) | first = S. | author-link = | title = குறுந்தொகை, பரிபாடல், கலித்தொகை [Kurunthogai, Paripadal, Kalitthogai] | publisher = Saradha Pathippagam | series = Sanga Ilakkiyam | volume = 2 | edition = 1 | date = August 2012 | location = Chennai | pages = 440 | language = Tamil | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> His head was said to be frightening enough to scare away a carcass-scavenging jackal, hence the given name.<ref name="Vedanayagam_Urai"/>
==Contribution to the Sangam literature== Nariveruvu Thalaiyar has written 5 Sangam verses, including 2 in [[Kurunthogai]] (verses 5 and 236), 2 in [[Purananuru]] (verses 5 and 195), and 1 in [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]] (verse 33).<ref name="SangaIlakkiyam_2"/>
